Consider a conductor of length&nbsp;\(l\)&nbsp;cutting through lines of a magnetic field of flux density&nbsp;\(B\)&nbsp;so an induced current&nbsp;\(I\)&nbsp;passes round the circuit.<br><ul><li>The conductor <b>experiences a force</b>&nbsp;\(F=BIl\)&nbsp;due to the current in a magnetic field. An&nbsp;<b>equal and opposite force</b>&nbsp;must be applied to keep it moving in the field.</li><li>The <b>work done</b> by applied force&nbsp;\(W=F\Delta s=BIl\Delta s\)</li><li>The <b>charge transferred</b> along the conductor in this time is&nbsp;\(Q=I\Delta t\)</li></ul><div>Therefore the induced emf is</div>\[\varepsilon=\frac{W}{Q}=\frac{F\Delta s}{Q}=\frac{BIl\Delta s}{I\Delta t}=\frac{Bl\Delta s}{\Delta t}\]